    "created_at": "2018-02-02T16:53:33Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-02-02T16:53:33Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@jorisvandenbossche you are right that (in my proposal 2) the support for ``names`` is only compelling for ``Index``, which is the only case in which we don't know what is going to come out.\r\n\r\nThis said, I think (although I don't think it is a priority) that\r\n- supporting ``names`` in all classes is just a matter of creating the decorator\r\n- we might want to support ``names`` e.g. in ``copy()``:\r\n``` python\r\nidx = Index(some_data_which_I_ignore, names=tuple_with_maybe_1_element)\r\nidx2 = idx.copy(names=another_tuple_with_maybe_1_element)\r\n```\r\n... and hence (presumably) also in the constructor\r\n- people _might_ reasonably expect that something that results (for instance) in a ``Int64Index`` (that is, ``Index()``) takes similar arguments than a ``Int64Index``, where applicable\r\n- I'm not claiming we should present (e.g. in the docs) ``name`` as an alias... it is just the way you _could_ see it if you want to \"think general\"\r\n\r\nBut again, I'm relatively indifferent on this."
  },
